65|5|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bakersfield, California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Kelly Paulsen\n|education    = [[St. Olaf College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website      = {{url|paulsen.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Erik Philip Paulsen''' (born May 14, 1965) is an American politician serving in the [[United States House of Representatives]] for {{ushr|MN|3}} since 2009. A member of the [[Republican Party of Minnesota]], he previously served in the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] from 1995 to 2009 and as [[Minnesota House Majority Leader|Majority Leader]] from 2003 to 2007. His district in the western part of the [[Minneapolis-St. Paul|Twin Cities]] metropolitan area includes [[Bloomington, Minnesota|Bloomington]], [[Eden Prairie]], [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], [[Minnetonka]], [[Maple Grove, Minnesota|Maple Grove]], [[Plymouth, Minnesota|Plymouth]] and [[Wayzata]].\n\n== Early life, education, and career ==\nBorn in [[Bakersfield, California]], Paulsen graduated from [[Chaska High School]] in Minnesota in 1983.<ref name=\"leg.state.mn.us\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leg.state.mn.us/legdb/fulldetail.aspx?id=10508 |title=Paulsen, Erik - Legislator Record - Minnesota Legislators Past & Present |publisher=Leg.state.mn.us |date= |accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[St. Olaf College]], and received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[mathematics]] in 1987. After college, Paulsen worked as an [[intern]] for Republican Senator [[Rudy Boschwitz]] from 1989 until Boschwitz was defeated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] challenger [[Paul Wellstone]] in 1990.<ref name=\"leg.state.mn.us\"/> Paulsen then took a staff position with Republican Representative [[Jim Ramstad]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] He worked on Ramstad's local congressional campaign in 1992 before seeking election to the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] in 1994.<ref name=\"legistorm.com\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090105163827/http://www.legistorm.com/blog/2008-election-big-for-former-congressional-staffers.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.leg.mn/legdb/fulldetail.asp?ID=10508 Minnesota Legislative Library for Erik Paulsen]</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to 2009, Paulsen worked as a part-time business analyst for [[Target Corporation]] while a member of the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"leg.state.mn.us\"/>\n\n== Minnesota House of Representatives ==\nPaulsen was initially elected as an [[Independent-Republican Party|Independent Republican]]. Before entering politics, he worked as a businessman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paulsen, Erik, (1965 - )|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000594 |publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=October 26, 2016}}</ref> He served on the Commerce and Labor, Rules and Legislative Administration, Taxes, and Ways and Means committees.<ref name=\"protege\">{{cite news |last=Duchschere |first=Kevin |title=Ramstad prot\u00e9g\u00e9 Paulsen announces House bid |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/south/14473002.html|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=January 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Erik Paulsen.jpg|thumb|Earlier official photo for Paulsen]]\n\n===Elections===\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2008#District 3}}\nPaulsen won a three-way race for Minnesota's Third Congressional District in November 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brunswick |first=Mark|last2=Furst|first2=Randy|title=Paulsen triumphs over Madia for Third District seat |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/house/33872049.html|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=November 5, 2008}}</ref> His U.S. House candidacy was announced after the incumbent, [[Jim Ramstad]] (a Republican), announced his retirement in 2007, which gave an opportunity for both major parties to field potential candidates. Shortly after he announced his retirement, Ramstad endorsed Paulsen and served as the chairman of Paulsen's Steering Committee.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081009000808/http://www.paulsenforcongress.com/index.asp?Type=B_EV&SEC=%7B988B9D2B-ACA9-49D0-937D-B4C8640D009B%7D&DE=%7B4E00262A-C198-41C3-8C0C-699D96BE2997%7D Ramstad endorses Erik Paulsen]</ref> Paulsen was a speaker at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].\n\nPaulsen won the election with 48.48% of the vote, to [[Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party]] nominee Ashwin Madia's 40.85% and  [[Independence Party of Minnesota]] candidate David Dillon's 10.56%. While not achieving a majority, Paulsen defeated Madia by about 30,000 votes.<ref>[http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/20081104/ElecRslts.asp?M=CG&CD=03 Minnesota Secretary of State] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122033131/http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/20081104/ElecRslts.asp?M=CG&CD=03 |date=November 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2010#District 3}}\nPaulsen won reelection with 59% of the vote against [[Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party]] challenger [[Jim Meffert]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2010/results/state/#MN | work=CNN | title=State Results \u2013 Election Center 2010 \u2013 Elections & Politics from CNN.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the race, Meffert filed a complaint with the [[United States House Committee on Ethics]] claiming that Paulsen distributed a deliberately misleading mailing to his constituents using the franking privilege afforded to House members. The committee didn't act on the complaint, as the franking office had cleared the mailer in advance.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wallbank |first=Derek |url=http://www.minnpost.com/derekwallbank/2011/04/28/27809/no_comment_the_story_of_an_ethics_complaint_and_what_didnt_happen_next |work=MinnPost|title=No Comment: The story of an ethics complaint and what didn't happen next|date=April 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2012#District 3}}\nPaulsen ran against DFL nominee Brian Barnes, an Edina businessman and former Navy Reserve officer. He was reelected with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewspapers.com/2012/11/06/erik-paulsen-wins-re-election-in-3rd-congressional-district/ |title=Erik Paulsen wins re-election in 3rd Congressional District &#124; Local News &#124; hometownsource.com |publisher=Abcnewspapers.com |date=November 6, 2012 |accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Minnesota's 3rd Congressional district election, 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/Results/USRepresentative/20|title=Results for All Congressional Districts, 2014 |publisher=Minnesota Secretary of State|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Erik Paulsen (Incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party of Minnesota\n| votes = 167,515\n| percentage = 62.14\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Sharon Sund\n| party = Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party\n| votes = 101,846\n| percentage = 37.78\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| candidate = Others\n| party = Write-in\n| votes = 224\n| percentage = 0.08\n}}\n{{Election box majority no change|\n|votes = 65,669\n|percentage = 24.36%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 269,585\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n | winner = Republican Party of Minnesota\n | loser = Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n====2016====\n{{Election box begin no change \n| title=Minnesota's 3rd Congressional district election, 2016 <ref name=\"Generalelection\">{{cite news |url=http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/Results/USRepresentative/100 |title=November 8, 2016 General Election Unofficial Results |date=November 8, 2016 |accessdate=February 26, 2018 |publisher=Minnesota Secretary of State }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party of Minnesota\n  |candidate  = Erik Paulsen\n  |votes      = 223,077\n  |percentage = 56.70\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party\n  |candidate  = [[Terri Bonoff]]\n  |votes      = 169,243\n  |percentage = 43.01\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n  |party      = \n  |candidate  = Write-in\n  |votes      = 1,144\n  |percentage = 0.29\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes      = 393,464\n  |percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n  | winner = Republican Party of Minnesota\n  | loser  = Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\nThe Bicameral Joint Economic Committee\n\nThe House Committee on Ways and Means\n\n\u2022 Subcommittee on Health\n\u2022 Subcommittee on Trade\n\n===Town halls===\nIn 2017, a group of constituents sought signatures on a petition asking Paulsen to hold public town hall meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swnewsmedia.com/eden_prairie_news/news/local/group-asks-paulsen-to-hold-town-hall-meetings/article_f74d9497-7951-5c97-b2c3-a2bb8433c41d.html|title=Group asks Paulsen to hold town hall meetings|access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2017 his campaign made only unannounced robo-calls with campaign aides screening questions, business tours, and private meetings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Golden|first1=Erin|title=Reps. Paulsen, Lewis under pressure over town halls |url=http://www.startribune.com/paulsen-lewis-under-pressure-over-town-halls/417095393/|accessdate=January 11, 2018|publisher=Star Tribune|date=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brooks |first1=Jennifer |title=Paulsen uses 'telephone town halls' to hear from constituents |url=http://www.startribune.com/to-reach-your-congressman-press-1-paulsen-uses-telephone-town-halls-to-hear-from-constituents/477992553/ |agency=Star Tribune |publisher=Star Tribune}}</ref> Paulsen was invited to attend a \"With or Without Him\" town hall meeting but declined the invitation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hirsi |first1=Ibrahim |title=Scenes from the 'With or Without' Erik Paulsen town hall (spoiler alert: it was without him) |url=https://www.minnpost.com/politics-policy/2017/02/scenes-or-without-erik-paulsen-town-hall-spoiler-alert-it-was-without-him |agency=Minn Post |publisher=Minn Post |date=2/24/2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2018, Paulsen held three in-person town hall meetings<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Esme |title=Rep. Paulsen Faces 3rd District Constituents In Town Hall Meetings |url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2018/05/30/erik-paulsen-town-hall-meetings/ |agency=CBS Minnesota |publisher=CBS Minnesota |date=5/30/2017}}</ref> in the 3rd district. During the events, he distanced himself from President Trump and congressional leaders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coolican |first1=Patrick |title=At town hall, Rep. Erik Paulsen parries tough questions, distances from Trump |url=http://www.startribune.com/u-s-rep-erik-paulsen-gets-tough-questions-at-town-hall/484082631/ |agency=Star Tribune |publisher=Star Tribune |date=5/30/2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nPaulsen is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> the [[Republican Study Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/about/membership|publisher=Republican Study Committee|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref> the [[Congressional Arts Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref> the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> and the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref> \n\nPaulsen opposed the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009]].<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll037.xml Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009] Office of the Clerk of the U.S. House of Representatives</ref> Paulsen voted against the James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/votes/111/house/2/550/?nyt=true|title=House Vote 550 \u2013 Passes 9/11 Health Care Bill|work=Pro Publica}}</ref> Paulsen introduced the Text a Tip Act to the House in 2010. The bill would have allowed users to send tips about crimes to a third party, removing all identifying information about the source before the police received the message.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=590459&keyword=&phrase=&contain=|title=Public Statements - The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|date=|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> The bill died in committee and was not adopted.<ref>{{cite web|author=Erik Paulsen|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h111-5913|title=Text a Tip Act of 2010 (2010; 111th Congress H.R. 5913)|publisher=GovTrack.us|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> \n\nPaulsen cosponsored a draft of the Small Business Assistance and Relief Act in 2010, to provide increased lending and aid for small businesses and ease their financial encumbrances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=590458&keyword=&phrase=&contain=|title=Public Statements - The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h111-5554|title=Text of H.R. 5554 (111th): Small Business Assistance and Relief Act of 2010 (Introduced version)|publisher=GovTrack.us|date=June 17, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}} \n\nPaulsen supports the special investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election and President Trump's [[dismissal of James Comey]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=Cody|title=Paulsen joins Democrats' call for independent Russia probe after Comey firing|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2017/05/10/paulsen-joins-democrats-call-for-independent-russia-probe-after-comey-firing|agency=MPR News|publisher=MPR News}}</ref> In February 2017, Paulsen voted against requesting President Donald Trump's tax returns from the Treasury Department.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/02/these-23-republicans-passed-on-a-chance-to-get-trumps-tax-returns/516768/|title=These 23 Republicans Passed on a Chance to Get Trump's Tax Returns |last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|newspaper=The Atlantic|accessdate=February 16, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[FiveThirtyEight]] has found that Paulsen votes with President Trump 98% of the time, and is the third-most partisan Republican in the House when compared to his district's voting patterns.<ref name=\"Five38\">[https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/house/ Tracking Congress in the Age of Trump], accessed September 25, 2018</ref><ref>https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/house/?ex_cid=rrpromo)</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nPaulsen helped to author the Republican tax reform of 2017, the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-gop-tax-law-writer-faces-skeptics-in-his-minnesota-district-1538991000|title=A GOP Tax-Law Writer Faces Skeptics in His Minnesota District|last=Rubin|first=Richard|date=2018-10-08|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nPaulsen supports continuing the [[Jobs and Growth Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2003|Bush-era tax cuts]] and global [[free trade]] agreements.<ref>Black, Eric. [http://www.minnpost.com/ericblack/2008/10/15/3888/erik_paulsen_on_tax_cuts_inflammatory_and_misleading Erik Paulsen on tax cuts: inflammatory and misleading.] ''Minn Post.'' October 15, 2008.</ref> He voted for the fiscal 2012 federal budget plan that provided for substantial overhaul of Medicare, including replacement of the traditional program with a premium support payment for private health insurance coverage for Americans under age 55.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2011-277|title=H.Con.Res. 34 (112th): Establishing the budget for the United States Government for fiscal year 2012 and setting forth appropriate budgetary ...|publisher=GovTrack.us|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}}\n\nPaulsen voted against the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]]<ref>[https://votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=23644&can_id=3833 Appropriations, Tax Law Amendments, and Unemployment Benefit Amendments (\"Stimulus Bill\")] ''Project Vote Smart''.<br/>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll070.xml]</ref> and [[Dodd-Frank]].<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll968.xml The Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act of 2009] Office of the Clerk of the U.S. House of Representatives</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nIn 2009, Paulsen expressed opposition to a [[public health insurance option]] and instead supported a Republican alternative plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2009/06/30/9908/minnesota_delegations_positions_on_health_care_plans |title=Minnesota delegation's positions on health care plans|publisher=MinnPost|date=June 30, 2009|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> At an April 7, 2010, Republican rally in Minneapolis, Paulsen described the Affordable Care Act as a \"government takeover of health care,\" a claim that [[Minnesota Public Radio]] said \"isn't correct.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/04/07/palin-bachmann-rally-fact-check/|title=Fact-checking yesterday's political rallies &#124; Minnesota Public Radio NewsQ|publisher=Minnesota.publicradio.org|date=April 8, 2010|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nPaulsen has voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll154.xml|title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 154|date=May 16, 2013|accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2015/roll058.xml|title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 58|date=February 3, 2015|accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref> In January 2017, he voted for the budget reconciliation provision to begin the process of ACA repeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/13/politics/house-obamacare-repeal-vote/ |title=House takes first step towards repealing Obamacare|publisher=cnn.com |date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Paulsen voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}<br/>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/05/04/health-care-vote-puts-pressure-dozens-vulnerable-gop-reps/101297824/|title=Health care vote puts pressure on dozens of vulnerable GOP reps|work=USA TODAY|accessdate=May 4, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Paulsen sponsored legislation to repeal caps on Medicare outpatient services like physical therapy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paulsen introduces legislation to permanently repeal Medicare cap on outpatient services|url=https://riponadvance.com/stories/paulsen-introduces-legislation-permanently-repeal-medicare-cap-outpatient-services/|agency=Ripon Advance|publisher=Ripon Advance|date=2/6/2017}}</ref>\n\nPaulsen introduced legislation to combat opioid abuse by educating seniors about non-opioid alternative pain treatments and ways to safely dispose of addictive painkillers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Committee gives nod to Erik Paulsen's opioid measure|url=http://www.swnewsmedia.com/eden_prairie_news/news/local/committee-gives-nod-to-erik-paulsen-s-opioid-measure/article_7b56fcd2-4662-52a8-b003-d574dc31a943.html|agency=SW Newsmedia|publisher=SW Newsmedia|date=5/17/18}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nPaulsen has been a longtime proponent of immigration reform and supports granting temporary legal status to those who were brought to the U.S. illegally as children,<ref>{{cite news|title=Minn. Congressman Erik Paulsen Pushes Bill To Protect DACA Recipients|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2017/12/06/paulsen-daca-bill/|publisher=CBS Minnesota|date=12/6/2017}}</ref> saying he supports \"ensuring that young people who came to the United States through no fault of their own and have done nothing wrong are able to be valuable contributors to our country.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Paulsen Statement on DACA|url=https://paulsen.house.gov/press-releases/paulsen-statement-on-daca/|website=Paulsen.house.gov}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Paulsen joined House Democrats in signing a \"discharge petition\" to force the House to vote on a series of immigration bills, including one that would provide permanent legal status to those who came to the country illegally as children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rao|first1=Maya|title=Paulsen joins effort to force House vote on Dreamers|url=http://m.startribune.com/paulsen-joins-effort-to-force-house-vote-on-dreamers/483519391/|agency=Star Tribune|publisher=Star Tribune|date=5/23/2018}}</ref>\n\nPaulsen does not support building a wall along the U.S. border with Mexico, citing its projected multi-billion-dollar cost.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sherry|first1=Allison|title=Paulsen, emboldened by full GOP rule but skeptical of Trump, tries to shape federal tax reform |url=http://www.startribune.com/paulsen-emboldened-by-full-gop-rule-but-skeptical-of-trump-tries-to-shape-federal-tax-reform/413969143/|agency=Star Tribune|publisher=Star Tribune|date=2/17/2017}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nPaulsen has a lifetime rating of 16% from the League of Conservation Voters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Hannah |title=With seat in jeopardy, Erik Paulsen suddenly becomes an environmentalist|url=http://citypages.com/news/with-seat-in-jeopardy-erik-paulsen-suddenly-becomes-an-environmentalist/488045531|accessdate=July 20, 2018|publisher=City Pages|date=July 13, 2018}}</ref> He has called for an end to Minnesota's ban on building [[nuclear power]] plants, saying that \"trying to meet our energy needs without using nuclear energy is a little bit like trying to row a boat with one oar.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scheck|first1=Tom|title=Reps. Paulsen and Walz call to lift ban on nuclear power|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2009/11/24/nuclear-power-plant-moratorium|accessdate=January 11, 2018|publisher=MPR News|date=November 24, 2009}}</ref> Along with 95% of Republicans and 17% of Democrats, he voted against the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]], which would have imposed a cap-and-trade system.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll477.xml HR 2454: American Clean Energy and Security Act] Office of the Clerk of the U.S. House of Representatives</ref>\n\nPaulsen voted against allowing copper-sulfide mining in the Boundary Waters Canoe Area.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kraker|first1=Dan|title=U.S. House OKs bill paving way for mining near Boundary Waters|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2017/11/30/us-house-approves-bill-to-pave-way-for-mining-near-boundary-waters|accessdate=30 May 2018|agency=MPR News|publisher=MPR News}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\nIn 2010, Paulsen voted against a bill repealing the U.S. military's \"[[don't ask, don't tell]]\" policy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hart Van Denburg|url=http://www.citypages.com/news/dadt-passes-house-with-help-from-walz-ellison-mccollum-and-oberstar-6556854|title=DADT passes House with help from Walz, Ellison, McCollum and Oberstar|publisher=City Pages}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he voted for an amendment that would have defunded transition-related healthcare for transgender soldiers in the military.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Birkey|url=http://thecolu.mn/31096/mn-gop-reps-lewis-paulsen-emmer-vote-deny-healthcare-transgender-troops|title=MN GOP Reps. Lewis, Paulsen, Emmer vote to deny healthcare for transgender troops|publisher=The Column|date=July 20, 2017|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Guns===\nFrom 2007 through 2018, Paulsen received $21,150 in campaign contributions from the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA), which has given him an \"A\" rating.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Aaron|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/national/nra-donations|title=Have your representatives in Congress received donations from the NRA?|publisher=Washington Post|date=October 5, 2017|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> As of June 2016, he had voted 13 times in opposition to bringing gun safety bills to the House floor.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zurowski|first1=Cory|title=Hired guns: How the NRA buys sway with Minnesota politicians|url=http://www.citypages.com/news/hired-guns-how-the-nra-buys-sway-with-minnesota-politicians-8361712|accessdate=21 March 2018|publisher=City Pages|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Paulsen said he would support a ban on bump stocks, strengthened background checks, a lifting of the ban on federal research for gun violence, and gun violence restraining orders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=Tim|title=ep. Paulsen backs bump stock ban, gun violence research|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2018/02/22/erik-paulsen-more-gun-violence-research-bump-stock-ban|accessdate=February 26, 2018|publisher=MPR News|date=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Paulsen co-sponsored the Jake Laird Act, which provides grants to encourage states to adopt gun violence restraining order laws. Gun violence restraining orders enable local law enforcement to seize and retain firearms from people who are determined to be an imminent danger to themselves or others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rao|first1=Maya|title=Rep. Erik Paulsen gets behind gun violence measure in Congress|url=http://www.startribune.com/rep-erik-paulsen-gets-behind-gun-violence-measure-in-congress/482327791/|agency=Star Tribune|publisher=Star Tribune}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Paulsen voted in favor of the Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act of 2017,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maya|first1=Rao|title=Push for gun permits across state lines concerns Minnesota law enforcement|url=http://www.startribune.com/push-for-gun-permits-across-state-lines-concerns-minnesota-law-enforcement/465038423/|agency=Star Tribune|publisher=Star Tribune|date=12/25/2017}}</ref> which allows people with a concealed carry permit in one state to legally travel with hidden guns to any other state.\n\n===Legislation===\nOn February 13, 2013, Paulsen introduced the [[National Park Service 100th Anniversary Commemorative Coin Act (H.R. 627; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]] to mint and issue [[gold]], [[silver]], and [[Half dollar (United States coin)|half-dollar]] clad coins in commemoration of the 100th anniversary of the establishment of the [[National Park Service]] (NPS).<ref name=627sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 627 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/627|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Pekow1>{{cite news|last=Pekow|first=Charles|title=House approves commemorative coins for National Park Service centennial|newspaper=The Examiner|date=April 30, 2014}}</ref> The coins would all have a surcharge attached, the money from which would be given to the [[National Park Foundation]].<ref name=\"Pekow1\"/>\n\nPaulsen strongly supported a bill that would make it easier for [[Non-bank financial institution|nonbank financial institutions]] such as [[Money services business|money service businesses]] to provide [[remittance]] payments internationally.<ref name=allAfricaMay7>{{cite news|last=Radio|first=Dalsan|title=Somalia: Congressman Ellison's Money Remittances Improvement Act Passed|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201405071137.html|accessdate=May 8, 2014|newspaper=All Africa|date=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Paulsen argued that the bill would make it easier for American immigrants \"supporting their extended families overseas\" to help their relatives, while still \"providing the necessary safeguards to ensure their money reaches its intended destination.\"<ref name=EllisonPRMay6>{{cite web|title=Ellison, Paulsen, Duffy Applaud Passage of Money Remittances Improvement Act|url=http://ellison.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/ellison-paulsen-duffy-applaud-passage-of-money-remittances-improvement|publisher=House Office of Keith Ellison|accessdate=May 8, 2014|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref> \n\nOn November 21, 2013, Paulsen introduced the [[Stop Exploitation Through Trafficking Act of 2013 (H.R. 3610; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would require each state, within three years, to have in effect legislation that: (1) treats a minor who has engaged or attempted to engage in a commercial sex act as a victim of a severe form of [[human trafficking|trafficking in persons]], (2) discourages the charging or prosecution of such an individual for a [[prostitution]] or sex trafficking offense, and (3) encourages the diversion of such individual to [[Child Protective Services|child protection services]].<ref name=3610sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3610 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3610|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref> The bill was scheduled to be voted on in the House on May 20, 2014 under a [[suspension of the rules]].<ref name=MarcosMay16>{{cite news |last=Marcos|first=Cristina|title=Next week: Lawmakers to debate defense and drones|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/scheduling/206363-next-week-defense-authorization-drones|accessdate=May 19, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith Democratic Senator [[Amy Klobuchar]], he led an effort to repeal an excise tax on medical devices imposed by the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. The bill passed the House one vote shy of a veto-proof majority.<ref>Brodey, Sam.[https://www.minnpost.com/politics-policy/2015/06/us-house-passes-repeal-medical-device-tax U.S. House passes repeal of medical device tax.] ''Minn Post.'' June 18, 2015.</ref> A two-year suspension of the tax was included in a 2015 year-end funding bill in 2015.<ref>Spencer, Jim. [http://www.startribune.com/device-tax-could-be-suspended-for-two-years-in-tax-deal/362660581/ Medical device tax could be suspended for two years in tax deal. ''Star Tribune.'' 16 December 2015.]</ref><ref name=\"npr.org\">Zdechlik, Mark. [https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2016/02/16/465978865/with-special-tax-suspended-medical-device-firms-reap-big-savings With Special Tax Suspended, Medical Device Firms Reap Big Savings. ''npr.'' 16 February 2016.]</ref><ref name=\"congress.gov\">[https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/2029?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22H+R+2029%22%5D%7D&resultIndex=1 H.R. 2029 - Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016. ''Congress.gov.'' 18 December 2015.]</ref><ref name=\"npr.org\"/><ref name=\"congress.gov\"/>\n\nAlso in 2015, Paulsen authored a bill to provide tax incentives to encourage food donations,<ref>Olson, Samantha. [http://www.medicaldaily.com/pulse/john-oliver-exposes-food-waste-america-billions-dollars-food-wasted-while-millions-343798 John Oliver Exposes Food Waste In America: Billions Of Dollars In Food Wasted While Millions Of People Go Hungry.] ''Medical Daily.'' July 20, 2015.</ref> and wrote a provision of the National Defense Authorization Act that requires the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] to return all military working dogs to the United States after completing their service.<ref>Keady, Cameron. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/military-dog-law-transportation-home_us_5665c0b1e4b079b2818f4cab Every U.S. Military Dog Will Be Brought Home, Thanks To New Law.] ''The Huffington Post.'' December 7, 2015.</ref> The [[American Humane Association]] strongly advocated for passage of this provision.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151204233937/http://www.americanhumane.org/about-us/newsroom/news-releases/american-humane-association-clinches-major-victory-for-military-dogs.html American Humane Association clinches major victory for military dogs.] ''American Humane Association.'' November 25, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDuring college at St. Olaf, Paulsen met his wife, Kelly. The Paulsens had four daughters as of 2014, and live in [[Eden Prairie, Minnesota|Eden Prairie]]. Paulsen serves as a board member of the Eden Prairie A Brighter Day Foundation, Habitat for Global Learning, Habitat for Technology and the Southdale YMCA. He is a member of the American Council of Young Political Leaders and the Eden Prairie Chamber of Commerce, and volunteers for Learning Exchange.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=3833 |title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 Representative Erik Paulsen \u2013 Biography |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=May 14, 1965 |accessdate=November 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nPaulsen has participated in the inaugural two-year class of the Aspen Rodel Fellowship in Public Leadership, the German Marshall Memorial Fellowship, the Young Leaders Forum of the National Committee on U.S.-China Relations, and the American Council of Young Political Leaders.<ref name=\"house1\">http://paulsen.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=98&sectiontree-2,98{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He has been granted an [[Aspen Institute]] Rodel Fellowship in Public Leadership, and a [[German Marshall Fund|Marshall Memorial Fellowship]] from the German Marshall Fund of the United States.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota]]\n* [[United States congressional delegations from Minnesota]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://paulsen.house.gov/ Congressman Erik Paulsen] official U.S. House website\n* [http://paulsenforcongress.com/ Erik Paulsen for Congress]\n* {{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Minnesota/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Erik_Paulsen_%5BR-3%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|erikpaulsen}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000594 | votesmart=3833 | fec=H8MN03077 | congress=erik-paulsen/1930 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-mn-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Pawlenty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Majority Leaders of the Minnesota House of Representatives|Majority Leader of the Minnesota House of Representatives]]|years=2003\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tony Sertich]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Ramstad]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Minnesota's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2009\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pat Tiberi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee|Joint Economic Committee]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pete Olson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representat